## CIP-0091: The Optimized Case Strategy

CIP-0091 notes that even before the proposal is adopted, there is an optimization available for forced builtins in UPLC:

> "One can bind the forced builtins to a variable at the outermost layer of the UPLC program and from there on just use the forced builtins."

This means instead of re-applying `force` every time a builtin is called within a program, you apply the forces **once** at the top level, bind the result to a variable, and reuse that variable. This turns a repeated O(n) cost into a one-time O(1) cost per execution.

## Equivalent Pattern in Aiken v3

Aiken encourages a similar pattern: compute repeated sub-expressions once and bind them to `let` variables, avoiding redundant work in the compiled UPLC.

```aiken
use aiken/collection/list
use aiken/crypto.{VerificationKeyHash}
use cardano/assets.{PolicyId}
use cardano/transaction.{Transaction}

validator optimized_multi_check(owners: List<VerificationKeyHash>) {
  mint(_redeemer: Void, policy_id: PolicyId, self: Transaction) -> Bool {
    // Bind once, reuse — mirrors the CIP-0091 "optimized case" philosophy
    let signatories = self.extra_signatories
    let minted = self.mint

    // Check that at least one owner signed
    let any_owner_signed =
      list.any(owners, fn(owner) { list.has(signatories, owner) })

    // Check that something was minted under this policy
    let policy_tokens = assets.tokens(minted, policy_id)
    let has_mint = !assets.is_zero(assets.from_asset_list([Pair(policy_id, assets.tokens(minted, policy_id) |> aiken/collection/dict.to_pairs)]))

    any_owner_signed
  }

  else(_) {
    fail
  }
}
```

The core principle from CIP-0091 applies at every level: **compute once, reuse many times** — whether it's a UPLC forced builtin or an Aiken `let` binding — to minimize wasted execution cycles and reduce on-chain costs.

